text: There's only a few film sagas that can be called successful adaptations of literary works. Peter Jackson's Lord of the Rings, the Harry Potter movies, Hunger Games saga... there might be a handful of others but most attempts fail. Few can keep making blockbusters for the decade or so that it takes to finish a large saga. There are four books in this one. Six if you count the in between ones. The Gunslinger already lost my attention as the trailer looks like someone threw the first two books, a collection of the comics and an old Steven Seagal flick into a blender and hit pur√©e. Idris Elba, Matthew McConaughey... what a wasted opportunity for these two great actors. This looks rushed and so I fear that it will fail at transitioning the original source into film. Best of luck.

text: Majority of comments:  "Lost interest when kids showed up"  It's based on a classic book that's ABOUT kids. Did you want them to up them to adults? Cuz that would be stupid.   "Oh great, ANOTHER female lead!"  Um, yea, the lead in the book was a girl. Did you want them to make her a guy just to make you feel better about your masculinity? Because that would be even more stupid.   "Forced diverse cast!"  Speculative. The director is black, so maybe, however I don't recall the book being specific on their race. If the characters were written basically race-neutral, then anything goes.   "They already did a movie of this!"  A television movie, which the book's author HATED. Who knows, maybe this version will please.   "Oprah = instant NOPE"  The Color Purple. Woman can act.   Tl;dr, know what you're talking about before you complain, and if you're going to criticize, criticize it on its own merits and how it compares to the book, instead of LOOKING for things to complain about.

text: I noticed there are¬†many who loves¬†using the racist card against others. But¬†If you¬†point out that none of the main characters were black in the novel, that's not being racist. It's about hypocrisy. Can you imagine if Disney used a novel written by a black author instead, and hired a white director who made some of the characters white? And for what reason? The director says she wanted Meg to look like one of the brown girls from her own childhood. True colorblindness is if your ethnicity is irrelevant. But she was very specific¬†about ethnicity and knew what she wanted.¬†Now, if Meg was black and a white director said he wanted her to look like one of the blonde girls from his childhood, people would go ballistic. Not that I know how bad of an actress she is, since I haven't seen her in other movies, but lots of people in the comment section are hinting that she's a bad actress in other movies. text: Chris Pine seems to be the only person expressing genuine emotion in the trailer, I found myself immediately affected and interested in his character. I can't say the same for the three witches though.   Oprah's face is too well known and her manner in this trailer was very much like the persona she often assumes in public i.e. dispenser of wisdom. I can't submerge Oprah and just see the character of the wise witch she is meant to be playing. The same for the glimpse we were shown of Reese Witherspoon - she just looked like an outlandishly dressed, stern looking version of herself. Now we all know that both of these ladies can act so this is either a failure of the director or a casting failure.   I certainly would have preferred to see unknown but deserving actresses cast in these roles but I suspect that Disney wanted "stars" who could open the movie.

text: Here is a very good book being made PC-compliant as a movie. This too shall fail. Great book that could have been at least a very good movie destroyed - once again - by Hollywood's pathological insistence that every movie be first and foremost, PC. We all know and most of us hate this routine.   Hollywood is in its death throes as a cultural icon and force in America. Soon the question will be, if Hollywood makes a movie, will anyone see it and who cares anyway?   The solution is not rocket science. It is rational human thought. Drop the PC, drop the politics, drop the biases are really pissing your customers off and just make entertaining movies and TV. Don't try to indoctrinate/educate us by degrading and condescending to the a huge portion of your audience. Not all of us are wracked with PC-guilt like so many elites seem to be. We just want to live and let live and watch a good freaking movie every once in a while.   How hard can that be Hollywood? You don't seem to have a clue right now. text: I have the book on my knee right now so I could look through it and have proof. Meg is definitely not supposed to be black and I'm not racist in the slightest, but this is one of my favorite books and they ruined it. The comments all say that It just says Meg has brown hair and doesn't specify on race. Well, it specifically decribes her mother as having flaming red hair, creamy skin, and violet eyes. It says Charles Wallace is a tiny blonde haired boy. And even in the movie they made her father white. The book says Charles should be white which he is not in the trailer, and if nobody knows specifically what Meg should look like, well if her mother is white and red haired of all things and her dad is white, how on earth is Meg supposed to be black? And aside from that, it just looks dreadful anyway. And Zach Galifinakis as the happy medium??? I wish this was a joke. I'm tired of them making movies from books and completely butchering it. It reminds of the Vampire Academy movie they made from the books. I can't even watch it because the acting blows and it's just terrible, they definitely ruined that too. Go ahead and say I'm racist, but it has nothing to do with race. They like to fuck it up to try to make everyone happy and end up making it so far from the actual book that the people that have actually read it get angry. Fuck this movie and Oprah Winfrey. If Meg was supposed to be black and said so in the book, I wouldn't have cared. But they're changing the book to make others happy and it needs to stop. It's like the fiasco with Disney wanting to give live action Mulan a white cast. THAT made me irate, because it's literally set in China and that's what it was all about, so of course they should have all been Chinese, or at least of Asian descent. Who seriously cares?? I just want the movies to be made as close to the books as possible, but no. That won't happen. Nobody should have gotten angry if they made the proper characters white because that's what they should be. This bullshit is getting ridiculous.

text: Switching a white character to be played by a black actress is not the same as the inverse because context is a thing and it matters. The ideal isn't that every character is performed as the race they're written in. The ideal is a world where source material has characters of many backgrounds, where lots of different sorts of little girls get to be in their favorite YA novel, or in its movie adaptation. The ideal world is one where actors get roles regardless of race, except for parts where race is a particular factor of character, and nobody ever bats an eye.   That's not our world yet, but none of you seem to want us to become more comfortable having roles race-switched, even in scenarios where it's switched to white (which is something people have an issue with because of *context* btw). You just want this to be played by a white girl. To "respect the source material." You want to justify how uncomfortable attempts at diversity make you.

text: For Christian viewers: The book(s?) that the movie is based upon is a tale of good vs. evil from a _humanistic_ world view, which doesn't directly oppose Christianity but is incompatible with it. (For instance, Jesus is presented as a "good man" but not the Son of God, along with several other equally "good men". Also, too much "sameness" is called an evil, though I think that's a personal preference, not an objective moral. I think it's laughable to hold "Variety is the spice of life" up to "Thou shalt not kill" or even "Thou shalt not steal.")  I only read the first book of the series, though I very much enjoyed the read; it was very well written. However, I was in eighth or ninth grade at the time and solid in my Christian faith and doctrine, so it was easy for me to dismiss the theological/mythical aspects to the story as hogwash, but younger children might be confused or even influenced by the story. Beware.  As for this film, clues seem to point to it having much more overt leftist ideology (SJW beliefs in particular) stuffed into it than the original source, so I cannot recommend this movie to anyone.

text: I understand the necessity for adaptation between books and films. What I don't understand is why we cannot have a single faithful attempt at adaptation of a modern young adult classic, that is, like A Wrinkle in Time.  If there was a fantastical book that did not need the flat, cartoonish CG, Alice in Wonderland treatment exhibited in this trailer, it is A Wrinkle in Time. The book is notable for its gravity and sense of place. The setting of the Murry homestead in rural New England forms a strong character of its own. That sense of place and reality, even in the fantastical settings, seems missing. The effects and cinematography seem more fitting for a Dr. Seuss, than a Madeleine L'Engle.   Who in their right mind thought that the Eurythmics "Sweet Dreams are Made of This" was the right tone for this work. I like the song, but for this? What were they thinking? The only reasonable conclusion that one can arrive at is that the ecthroi are still with us.

text: I honestly feel like I'm the only one here who is actually thankful they just now decided to go back on "A Wrinkle in Time" and try to undo wrongs the previous films had suffered. No joke this was my absolute favorite book as a kid and recently did a senior art project on the book. Basically made concept art for what an animated film of it might look like. For me the celebrity casting or diverse ethnicities I could give less of a fuck about (I don't know if they ever said what color the characters were besides from the front covers so I'm fine with it). What's important is how well they actually stick to the original story, character personalities, and settings. Don't understand why they changed Ms.Whatsit's centaur form though. Guess it's to bring out the fantasy aspect. Will withhold major judgment till I see the movie for myself.

text: This movie is a representation of what the ancient Platonic, Egyptian and Sumerian philosopher priests considered the afterlife to be: a confrontation between illusory darkness that attempts to force you to defeat yourself with your own weaknesses.  Fail and you return to Earth, reincarnated in a new body without your memories. Until you get it right.  The snake eating its own tail, the dragon who when he is done digesting us, shits us out back into its mouth to eat us again, unless you "Be a warrior", the Ouroborus.  Consider that this film may be an esoteric nod to the ancient religions and not just some sci-fi mistake starring Oprah. Just a thought.

text: SPOILERS AHEAD, MAJOR SPOILERS AHEAD! ONLY READ IF YOU'VE FINISHED THE BOOK OR WATCHED THE MOVIE!     Ok, after I read the part in the book where Meg meets those creatures after saving her dad and tries to explain color to them, I took a shower (which actually kind of helps you think). I think that if I had to explain color to a blind person, I would relate colors with touch or emotion. Yellow is the color of warmth, sunlight and happiness. White is the color of purity. Black is the color of fear and the unknown. Green is the color of life and prosperity. As I went on and on through the colors, I realized that, if you thought about color this way, a rainbow was the perfect equilibrium between emotions. The equilibrium between life and death, darkness and light. I guess you could say a rainbow is... The Force üòè
